Lots with third-party guarantees (or irrevocable bids, as Sotheby=E2=80=99s=
 calls them) did well, too. Richard Prince=E2=80=99s Nurse on Trial, from 2=
005, was estimated at $5 million but hammered at $6 million, for a $7.2 mil=
lion selling price. There were at least three bidders on the work, includin=
g the guarantor. Miyoko Ito=E2=80=99s haunting Sunbather, from 1966-68, had=
 a low $150,000 estimate, an irrevocable bid, and five or six bidders who d=
rove the hammer price to $450,000=E2=80=94three times the estimate. Another=
 de Kooning, from 1982, with a high estimate at $9 million and an irrevocab=
le bid, eked out additional bids to hammer at $9.4 million. Ed Ruscha=E2=80=
=99s George=E2=80=99s Flag was estimated at $8 million. It, too, had an irr=
evocable bid, which seems to have attracted interest, because it hammered a=
t $13 million and became the
top lot of the sale, making $13.65 million=E2=80=94a price that indicates t=
he work was bought by the irrevocable bidder.

The unsung success of the Sotheby=E2=80=99s evening sale was the run of six=
 works from Dorothy Lichtenstein=E2=80=99s estate. The various paintings, s=
culptures, and a print were estimated well, yet each work exceeded the esti=
mate, revealing demand for Lichtenstein previously not seen in the market a=
nd certainly not the night after at Christie=E2=80=99s.

Meanwhile, in Midtown=E2=80=A6

Back at Christie=E2=80=99s for the final evening sale of the cycle, I wasn=
=E2=80=99t expecting much. After all, the week seemed to be mostly about ex=
ceptional works, and there were few =E2=80=9Cmasterpieces=E2=80=9D in this =
sale.

Still, there was the David Hammons Flight Fantasy work that was priced at $=
2 million and got bid to $3.2 million by several women in the room. Cecily =
Brown=E2=80=99s The Butcher and the Policeman, from 2013, hardly qualifies =
as a masterpiece within her body of work. As I heard one person say, =E2=80=
=9CThere are so many other things to spend $4 million on.=E2=80=9D But that=
 didn=E2=80=99t stop bidders=E2=80=94including some art advisors who traffi=
c in Brown=E2=80=99s work=E2=80=94from pushing the painting to a $4.9 milli=
on hammer, $5.97 million with fees. Brown now has 10 works that have sold a=
t auction for between $5.8 million and $6.7 million, all in the
past six years. It=E2=80=99s a tight band for her top auction prices.

Rudolf Stingel also finally found some market footing at Christie=E2=80=99s=
=2E His self-portrait, from 2007, was e=
stimated at $1.8 million, but sold to=20=
the third-party guarantor for a $1.7 million hammer. That might sound disap=
pointing, but the Stingel market has been disorganized for years, a victim =
of several converging forces including the fraudster Inigo Philbrick=E2=80=
=99s heavy trafficking in the artist. Still, the last lot in Christie=E2=80=
=99s sale was another Stingel, a carpet painting from 2010, that had been o=
wned by the great collector Rosa de la Cruz. The buyer paid $945,000, solid=
ly above the $600,000 estimate, which was supported by a third-party guaran=
tee. When I spoke to the buyer=E2=80=99s advisor, who was the one bidding i=
n the room, the advisor shrugged and defended the purchase by saying, =E2=
=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s a great artist=E2=80=94and the prices are finally down t=
o where they should be.=E2=80=9D

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

I=E2=80=99ve got a lot more details and some behind-the-scenes stories to a=
dd to this basic account of the week. I=E2=80=99ll try to get to all of tha=
t on Tuesday, along with the data. In the meantime, I=E2=80=99m going to as=
sume you=E2=80=99ve read Vulture=E2=80=99s wild take ( https://www.vulture.=
com/article/new-jersey-artist-jamian-juliano-villani-gagosian-painting-inte=
