          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Christie=E2=80=99s =
C.E.O. <b>Guillaume Cerutti</b> was his usual Gallic self after the auction=
 house concluded its first evening of sales=E2=80=94led by a $121 million <=
b>Magritte</b>, a $68 million <b>Ed Ruscha</b>, a $26 million <b>Alberto Gi=
acometti</b>, a $19 million <b>David Hockney</b>, and a $17 million <b>Joan=
 Mitchell</b>. He sat stone-faced in the audience of his own post-sale pres=
s conference as chairman <b>Alex Rotter</b> explained that his approach to =
the season was to confront an uncertain market with undeniable masterpieces=
, top-loading the sales with bankable, evergreen art works. And that=E2=80=
=99s more or less how the first night played out: The top 10 lots of the <b=
>Mica Ertegun</b> and 20th Century sales accounted for <i>two-thirds</i> of=
 the $486 million in sales.<br/><br/>The following evening, shortly before =
Christie=E2=80=99s second sale on
Thursday, I caught up with an influential art advisor in the Christie=E2=80=
=99s lobby who observed that we seemed to be seeing a reemergence of =E2=80=
=9Cindividual taste.=E2=80=9D This was a polite way of saying that you real=
ly could not predict which lots would do well once you stepped down from th=
e undeniably great ones. Indeed, as I settled in to watch Christie=E2=80=99=
s 21st Century sale, I was prepared for a spotty night to end the spotty we=
ek that lurked beneath the headlines. <br/><br/>But at the end of Christie=
=E2=80=99s second evening, where all 42 lots offered were sold and only two=
 were withdrawn, Cerutti approached the press area to declare the evening=
=E2=80=99s $106.5 million sale=E2=80=94with only one work sold above $10 mi=
llion=E2=80=94a raging success. =E2=80=9CWrite about <i>that</i>,=E2=80=9D =
Cerutti said. Later, outside the sale room, he embraced <b>Kat Widing</b>, =
the head of sales, who was wearing an emerald green dress with a matching c=
ape. I=E2=80=99m not sure I=E2=80=99ve seen Cerutti in a better mood.
<br/><br/>Cerutti=E2=80=99s enthusiasm was a bit puzzling, however. Christi=
e=E2=80=99s $106.5 million sale was lower than the $112 million second even=
ing sale across town at Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the night before. To achieve a 1=
00 percent sell-through rate, Christie=E2=80=99s team got the consignors on=
 a third of the lots to lower their expectations. Yet, in the end, the sale=
 posted a hammer ratio=E2=80=94a measure of the enthusiasm of bidders (and =
thus the market)=E2=80=94of 1.16, which is much stronger than we=E2=80=99ve=
 seen in several seasons. And that may have been what Cerutti was most prou=
d of: His team took on a tough market and, seemingly, prevailed. <br/></td>
